are we right now?

499
00:26:33,725 --> 00:26:38,287
On the day that General Motors
declared Chapter 1 1 bankruptcy,

500
00:26:38,330 --> 00:26:41,766
I went with my dad to visit
the AC Spark Plug plant

501
00:26:41,800 --> 00:26:44,394
where he had worked
for over 30 years.

502
00:26:44,436 --> 00:26:48,099
- So you worked actually right here.
- You'd have to go--

503
00:26:48,139 --> 00:26:51,939
they had a ramp that took you
up over that, just beyond that...

504
00:26:51,977 --> 00:26:53,501
- Just beyond that space there?
- Yeah.

505
00:26:53,545 --> 00:26:55,536
- And then the factory was all over there?
- Yeah.

506
00:26:55,580 --> 00:26:57,980
Moore: The whole complex
is, like, two miles long.

507
00:26:58,016 --> 00:27:00,348
I remember Mom bringing
us kids in to pick you up.

508
00:27:00,385 --> 00:27:02,285
- 2:30 every day.
- Yeah, uh-huh.

509
00:27:02,320 --> 00:27:05,346
You'd walk out of there,
right over in there in fact.

510
00:27:05,390 --> 00:27:07,358
And we'd be waiting
in the car for you

511
00:27:07,392 --> 00:27:09,883
and we'd see you
come down the ramp.

512
00:27:09,928 --> 00:27:13,523
We got real excited
every time we saw you.

513
00:27:13,565 --> 00:27:16,056
I was there 33 1/2 years.

514
00:27:16,101 --> 00:27:18,160
- 33 1/2 years?
- Uh-huh.

515
00:27:18,203 --> 00:27:21,001
Moore: What's your best memory here,
being here, working here?

516
00:27:21,039 --> 00:27:24,202
My best memory?
I think the people.

517
00:27:24,242 --> 00:27:26,233
They were a really good bunch.

518
00:27:26,277 --> 00:27:29,144
- You liked the crowd you worked with?
- Yeah.

519
00:27:29,180 --> 00:27:32,445
Frank Moore:
A good place to work. I enjoyed it.

520
00:27:32,484 --> 00:27:35,351
But I'm sorry to see it go.

521
00:27:42,961 --> 00:27:45,691
Moore:
Shortly before Christmas 2008,

522
00:27:45,730 --> 00:27:48,858
Republic Windows & Doors
in Chicago, lllinois,

523
00:27:48,900 --> 00:27:52,131
abruptly fired
its entire unionized workforce

524
00:27:52,170 --> 00:27:55,230
of over 250 people.

525
00:27:55,273 --> 00:27:58,731
They were given
only three days' notice.

526
00:27:58,777 --> 00:28:00,836
Bank of America
would no longer provide

527
00:28:00,879 --> 00:28:03,074
a line of credit to the company,

528
00:28:03,114 --> 00:28:07,210
and so the workers were not paid
the money owed to them.

529
00:28:07,252 --> 00:28:10,050
Man #1 : My life revolves
around this job.

530
00:28:10,088 --> 00:28:14,252
I live according to my obligation
to my job, you know?

531
00:28:14,292 --> 00:28:18,353
And it's not just me,
it's all of the workers here.

532
00:28:18,396 --> 00:28:21,194
We go above and beyond

533
00:28:21,232 --> 00:28:23,826
the call of duty for Republic.

534
00:28:23,868 --> 00:28:26,598
And  attheend

535
00:28:26,638 --> 00:28:29,471
Republic cares nothing for us.

536
00:28:31,309 --> 00:28:34,278
Man #2: We found out that
they're gonna shut the plant on Tuesday.

537
00:28:34,312 --> 00:28:37,543
We don't deserve what
they're doing to us, you know?

538
00:28:37,582 --> 00:28:40,881
It really hurts because,
like I said,

539
00:28:40,919 --> 00:28:42,887
this is my second family.

540
00:28:42,921 --> 00:28:45,515
So it was-- it really hurts.
It really hurts.

541
00:28:45,557 --> 00:28:49,459
I'm gonna miss
all of them, you know?

542
00:28:49,494 --> 00:28:52,463
I'm gonna miss them
and I don't think

543
00:28:52,497 --> 00:28:54,829
anybody on this planet

544
00:28:54,866 --> 00:28:58,097
deserves what they've done to us.

545
00:29:05,577 --> 00:29:07,636
Moore: Scenes like this
were being repeated

546
00:29:07,679 --> 00:29:11,740
all over the country,
and no one seemed to mind.

547
00:29:11,783 --> 00:29:14,183
Zambezi, Zambezi

548
00:29:14,219 --> 00:29:17,347
-  Zambezi, Zam.
- Woman: Whoo!

549
00:29:17,388 --> 00:29:21,256
Moore: The president was enjoying
his final year in office.

550
00:29:21,292 --> 00:29:23,590
But as the economy
started to fall apart,

551
00:29:23,628 --> 00:29:27,758
he decided it was time
to roll out the C word.

552
00:29:27,799 --> 00:29:30,825
Capitalism is the best system
ever devised.

553
00:29:30,869 --> 00:29:32,268
Moore:
Huh. Really?

554
00:29:32,303 --> 00:29:35,568
Voices from the left and right
are equating the free enterprise system

555
00:29:35,607 --> 00:29:39,270
with greed and exploitation
and failure.

556
00:29:39,310 --> 00:29:41,301
Moore:
Hmm, greed,

557
00:29:41,346 --> 00:29:44,509
exploitation, failure?

558
00:29:44,549 --> 00:29:46,073
Go on, I'm listening.

559
00:29:46,117 --> 00:29:50,986
Capitalism offers people
the freedom to choose

560
00:29:51,022 --> 00:29:53,582
where they work
and what they do...

561
00:29:53,625 --> 00:29:56,321
Reporter: Pat Andrews
has been looking for work.

562
00:29:56,361 --> 00:30:00,229
Every morning she scans
the classifieds in vain.

563
00:30:00,265 --> 00:30:02,028
There isn't anything in here.

564
00:30:02,066 --> 00:30:05,001
I'm not gonna be a gentleman's club
hired dancer either.

565
00:30:06,337 --> 00:30:09,829
...the opportunity to buy
or sell products they want.

566
00:30:09,874 --> 00:30:11,808
Reporter: Tom Rendon
has avoided layoffs

567
00:30:11,843 --> 00:30:14,505
at his sign company
in Stockton, California,

568
00:30:14,546 --> 00:30:16,446
all because this one word
now makes up

569
00:30:16,481 --> 00:30:18,540
for half his business.

570
00:30:18,583 --> 00:30:22,144
If you seek social justice
and human dignity,

571
00:30:22,187 --> 00:30:26,021
the free market system
is the way to go.

572
00:30:26,057 --> 00:30:27,752
( applause )

573
00:30:28,893 --> 00:30:32,021
Moore: And for those seeking
justice in Pennsylvania,

574
00:30:32,063 --> 00:30:35,965
free enterprise
was definitely the way to go.

575
00:30:39,470 --> 00:30:41,131
Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania,

576
00:30:41,172 --> 00:30:43,333
has one of the highest rates
in the state

577
00:30:43,374 --> 00:30:47,003
of young people locked up
in the juvenile home.

578
00:30:47,045 --> 00:30:49,377
Perhaps it's because
the good people here

579
00:30:49,414 --> 00:30:51,780
employ the practices
of capitalism

580
00:30:51,816 --> 00:30:55,047
in dealing with
their wayward youth.

581
00:30:55,086 --> 00:30:57,987
The county hired a private
profit-making corporation

582
00:30:58,022 --> 00:31:02,152
with a sweet-sounding name,
PA Child Care.

583
00:31:03,394 --> 00:31:06,329
It was owned and run
by two businessmen,

584
00:31:06,364 --> 00:31:11,028
one of whom was Robert Powell,
an attorney and entrepreneur.

585
00:31:11,069 --> 00:31:13,003
His good friend Judge Conahan

586
00:31:13,037 --> 00:31:15,403
closed down
the public juvenile home

587
00:31:15,440 --> 00:31:17,374
and then got
PA Child Care to build

588
00:31:17,408 --> 00:31:20,571
an $8 million
privately-owned facility

589
00:31:20,612 --> 00:31:22,512
and charge it back to the county

590
00:31:22,547 --> 00:31:25,243
for a mere $58 million lease.

591
00:31:27,185 --> 00:31:30,814
Let's meet some of Wilkes-Barre's
juvenile delinquents.

592
00:31:30,855 --> 00:31:33,153
Magee smoked pot
at a high school party.

593
00:31:33,191 --> 00:31:36,422
I was very rebellious
when I was at this age.

594
00:31:36,461 --> 00:31:39,259
Moore: Matt, he got into
an argument at the dinner table.

595
00:31:39,297 --> 00:31:41,959
I threw a piece of meat,
as in steak,

596
00:31:42,000 --> 00:31:44,468
cooked dinner,
at my mother's boyfriend.

597
00:31:44,502 --> 00:31:46,868
Moore: Jamie got in a fight
at a shopping mall

598
00:31:46,905 --> 00:31:48,167
with her best friend.

599
00:31:48,206 --> 00:31:51,642
I just figured, you know, we just weren't
gonna be friends anymore.

600
00:31:51,676 --> 00:31:54,201
Moore: And Hillary made
a MySpace page

601
00:31:54,245 --> 00:31:56,406
making fun
of her assistant principal

602
00:31:56,447 --> 00:31:58,938
for being strict and having
no sense of humor.

603
00:31:58,983 --> 00:32:02,419
And it said some pretty silly,
like, 14-year-old-girl stuff.

604
00:32:02,453 --> 00:32:06,184
Moore: Her assistant principal
called the police.

605
00:32:06,224 --> 00:32:10,524
They all appeared before
kindly Judge Mark Ciavarella.

606
00:32:10,561 --> 00:32:13,291
These kids were about
to get their first lesson

607
00:32:13,331 --> 00:32:15,299
in American capitalism:

608
00:32:15,333 --> 00:32:20,134
time is money, lots of money.

609
00:32:20,171 --> 00:32:23,470
I went in front of the court,
in front of Mr. Ciavarella,

610
00:32:23,508 --> 00:32:25,305
and I wasn't even in front of him
for four minutes.

611
00:32:25,343 --> 00:32:27,436
I was only in front of him
for, like, two minutes.

612
00:32:27,478 --> 00:32:31,107
Hillary: The first thing that
Judge Ciavarella said to me was,

613
00:32:31,149 --> 00:32:34,016
"What makes you think
you can do this kind of crap?"

614
00:32:34,052 --> 00:32:36,486
I'm sure he knew in his mind
when I walked in

615
00:32:36,521 --> 00:32:38,284
that he was locking this kid up
no matter what.

616
00:32:38,323 --> 00:32:39,620
He didn't even look at me.

617
00:32:39,657 --> 00:32:42,626
Once I entered the courtroom,
I didn't have any chance.

618
00:32:42,660 --> 00:32:44,924
There was about six kids
who went in front of me.

619
00:32:44,963 --> 00:32:46,988
Every single kid who went
in front of Ciavarella,

620
00:32:47,031 --> 00:32:50,398
for all different reasons--
some minor, some serious--

621
00:32:50,435 --> 00:32:52,130
got sent away.

622
00:32:52,170 --> 00:32:56,072
Moore: Although Wilkes-Barre is located
in the United States of America,

623
00:32:56,107 --> 00:33:00,237
here capitalism
trumped democracy.

624
00:33:00,278 --> 00:33:03,509
Robert Powell, one of the owners
of PA Child Care,

625
00:33:03,548 --> 00:33:07,951
cut a business deal with Judge Conahan
and Judge Ciavarella.

626
00:33:07,986 --> 00:33:11,422
Judge Ciavarella then stepped up
his conviction rates.

627
00:33:11,456 --> 00:33:13,185
Many of these kids
were funneled

628
00:33:13,224 --> 00:33:17,991
into PA Child Care's
for-profit juvenile facility.

629
00:33:18,029 --> 00:33:19,428
Andfor theirtroubles,

630
00:33:19,464 --> 00:33:23,662
the judges received
over $2.6 million

631
00:33:23,701 --> 00:33:27,660
while the owners of PA Child Care
received tens of millions

632
00:33:27,705 --> 00:33:30,299
of taxpayer dollars
from the county.

633
00:33:30,341 --> 00:33:33,469
And where did Powell go
to enjoy all that money?

634
00:33:33,511 --> 00:33:35,706
On his private plane

635
00:33:35,747 --> 00:33:38,807
and his yacht,
the "Reel Justice."

636
00:33:40,485 --> 00:33:45,388
6,500 children
were unjustly convicted.

637
00:33:45,423 --> 00:33:48,824
It was good business
while it lasted.

638
00:33:49,961 --> 00:33:52,828
Reporter #1 : Two Luzerne County
judges in big trouble with the law.

639
00:33:52,864 --> 00:33:53,853
They're going to jail.

640
00:33:53,898 --> 00:33:55,331
Reporter #2:
Some kids were locked up

641
00:33:55,366 --> 00:33:59,632
even when probation officers
objected to detention.

642
00:33:59,670 --> 00:34:02,662
In there you lose track of time
and you lose track of the date.

643
00:34:02,707 --> 00:34:03,935
I was barely keeping track.

644
00:34:03,975 --> 00:34:07,103
It was supposed to be, like--
I believe it was, like, two months.

645
00:34:07,145 --> 00:34:09,545
And it went from two months
to nine months.

646
00:34:09,580 --> 00:34:12,276
He said originally
three to six months,

647
00:34:12,316 --> 00:34:16,309
but somehow I ended up
being there 11 1/2 months

648
00:34:16,354 --> 00:34:19,187
and I never went back
in front of the judge at all

649
00:34:19,223 --> 00:34:20,850
for him to give me extensions.

650
00:34:20,892 --> 00:34:22,689
Moore:
Not only did PA Child Care

651
00:34:22,727 --> 00:34:25,560
pay off the judges
to fill their cells,

652
00:34:25,596 --> 00:34:28,258
but their employees were the ones
who got to decide

653
00:34:28,299 --> 00:34:31,700
when a child had
enough rehabilitation.

654
00:34:31,736 --> 00:34:35,069
But that makes sense,
because any time a governmental unit

655
00:34:35,106 --> 00:34:37,666
turns over to
a profit-making corporation

656
00:34:37,708 --> 00:34:40,108
the duties it should be performing,

657
00:34:40,144 --> 00:34:42,169
what do you expect to happen?

658
00:34:42,213 --> 00:34:44,807
Matt: It makes me feel like
an item that they just used

659
00:34:44,849 --> 00:34:47,249
to just get money
and then tossed me aside.

660
00:34:47,285 --> 00:34:51,745
I'm just trying
to work on my flying

661
00:34:51,789 --> 00:34:53,984
and just trying to prepare
for my future

662
00:34:54,025 --> 00:34:57,256
so I can put this all behind me,
finally be done with all this.

663
00:34:57,295 --> 00:34:59,763
During the whole trial
I wasn't in control at all,

664
00:34:59,797 --> 00:35:02,231
but with flying it's only me.

665
00:35:02,266 --> 00:35:04,734
It's just that I just get
to do everything by myself.

666
00:35:04,769 --> 00:35:06,794
I'm the only one on the control.

667
00:35:06,838 --> 00:35:08,669
Moore:
Matt loves to fly

668
00:35:08,706 --> 00:35:11,971
and hopes to become
a pilot someday.

669
00:35:12,009 --> 00:35:14,637
If he does,
he'll get his second lesson

670
00:35:14,679 --> 00:35:17,273
in capitalism:

671
00:35:17,315 --> 00:35:20,341
that in America,
sometimes you're better off

672
00:35:20,384 --> 00:35:22,820
working at Mickey D's.

673
00:35:22,820 --> 00:35:25,380
- ( applause, cheering )
- Remember Sully?

674
00:35:25,423 --> 00:35:26,754
Captain Sullenberger,

675
00:35:26,791 --> 00:35:29,817
who safely landed an airbus
in the Hudson River

676
00:35:29,861 --> 00:35:32,887
- saving the lives of 150 passengers?
- ( patriotic music playing )

677
00:35:32,930 --> 00:35:35,797
- Man: A true American hero.
- ( applause )

678
00:35:38,936 --> 00:35:41,837
Moore: He met the mayor.
He went to the State of the Union.

679
00:35:41,873 --> 00:35:44,569
Heck, he even went
to the Super Bowl.

680
00:35:44,609 --> 00:35:46,839
Andthen hewenttoCongress.

681
00:35:46,878 --> 00:35:49,938
Sullenberger:
Flying has been my lifelong passion.

682
00:35:49,981 --> 00:35:52,142
But while I love my profession,

683
00:35:52,183 --> 00:35:54,879
I do not like
what has happened to it.

684
00:35:54,919 --> 00:35:57,012
- ( music halts )
- It is my personal experience

685
00:35:57,054 --> 00:36:00,251
that my decision to remain
in the profession I love

686
00:36:00,291 --> 00:36:04,921
has come at a great financial cost
to me and to my family.

687
00:36:04,962 --> 00:36:07,226
My pay has been cut 40%.

688
00:36:07,265 --> 00:36:10,928
My pension, like most airline pensions,
has been terminated.

689
00:36:10,968 --> 00:36:14,495
So please do not think I exaggerate
when I say that I do not know

690
00:36:14,539 --> 00:36:17,838
a single professional airline pilot
who wants his or her children

691
00:36:17,875 --> 00:36:19,467
to follow in their footsteps.

692
00:36:19,510 --> 00:36:22,240
Moore: Whoa, you cleared
the room with that one, Sully.

693
00:36:22,280 --> 00:36:24,578
I don't think the congressmen
wanted to hear that stuff.

694
00:36:24,615 --> 00:36:27,550
- They like you as a hero.
- The current experience...

695
00:36:27,585 --> 00:36:30,076
( patriotic music over dialogue )

696
00:36:42,133 --> 00:36:44,192
Moore: What was
your starting pay as a pilot?

697
00:36:44,235 --> 00:36:46,533
I made $19,000 the first year.

698
00:36:46,571 --> 00:36:50,029
I was bumped up to about 22,000
or 23,000 the second year.

699
00:36:50,074 --> 00:36:52,702
Last year, gross pay

700
00:36:52,743 --> 00:36:55,177
I made $17,600.

701
00:36:55,213 --> 00:36:57,807
There's a joke in the airline
when we get our wings pinned on us

702
00:36:57,848 --> 00:37:01,306
as new-hire airline pilots
that the company just kinda says,

703
00:37:01,352 --> 00:37:04,116
"Hey, don't apply for food stamps
in your uniform."

704
00:37:04,155 --> 00:37:07,022
Moore: I don't know about you,
but I want the pilot

705
00:37:07,058 --> 00:37:10,858
who's got me 30,000 feet up in the air
to be paid really well

706
00:37:10,895 --> 00:37:13,955
and not sitting up in the cockpit
digging through the pilot's seat

707
00:37:13,998 --> 00:37:15,989
Iooking for loose change.

708
00:37:16,033 --> 00:37:18,001
There was a period
of about four months

709
00:37:18,035 --> 00:37:20,799
where I was on food stamps.

710
00:37:20,838 --> 00:37:22,328
- You were on food stamps?
- Yes.

711
00:37:22,373 --> 00:37:25,137
- And you were still flying the plane?
- Yes.

712
00:37:25,176 --> 00:37:27,542
With my--
with my food stamp card.

713
00:37:27,578 --> 00:37:30,342
The lady I talked to
in the food stamp office,

714
00:37:30,381 --> 00:37:33,316
when I told her I was a pilot,
she didn't bat an eye,

715
00:37:33,351 --> 00:37:35,683
but she didn't--
I knew she didn't believe me.

716
00:37:35,720 --> 00:37:38,348
Moore: How have you gotten by?
How have you been able to afford things?

717
00:37:38,389 --> 00:37:40,983
Relying on credit cards
to buy the groceries at times

718
00:37:41,025 --> 00:37:42,754
- when I wasn't on food stamps.
- Oh, really?

719
00:37:42,793 --> 00:37:45,091
I have about $10,000
in credit card debt

720
00:37:45,129 --> 00:37:47,120
just on the necessities,

721
00:37:47,164 --> 00:37:49,724
not on the big-screen TV
and the stereo.

722
00:37:49,767 --> 00:37:52,964
Moore: You're using it
to buy your groceries and get by.

723
00:37:53,004 --> 00:37:54,938
- Yes.
- Do you have any student loan debt?

724
00:37:54,972 --> 00:37:56,667
- Yes.
- How much?

725
00:37:56,707 --> 00:37:58,265
Mine is about 80,000.

726
00:37:58,309 --> 00:38:01,710
- I took out $100,000.
- Moore: Student loans?

727
00:38:01,746 --> 00:38:04,613
And by the time I pay it back,
at this rate,

728
00:38:04,649 --> 00:38:07,015
it'll probably cost me well over
a half a million with interest

729
00:38:07,051 --> 00:38:09,611
and fees and penalties.

730
00:38:09,654 --> 00:38:11,884
It's something that I don't--
I don't like to spend a lot of time

731
00:38:11,922 --> 00:38:13,617
thinking about
because it's abysmal.

732
00:38:13,658 --> 00:38:16,126
It's one way that I get down
really quickly

733
00:38:16,160 --> 00:38:17,821
about my chosen career field

734
00:38:17,862 --> 00:38:20,296
is to think about how much I owe
and how little I make.

735
00:38:20,331 --> 00:38:23,232
Moore: Have you had to work
